Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setNet(25.10)                                                    setNet(25.10)

Name
       setNet - Marks the specified nets and their related pins as either spe-
       cial nets and pins, or regular nets and pins

Syntax
       setNet

       [-help]

       {-net <netName> | -file <fileName>}

       [-setTermSpecial]

       -type {regular | special}

       Marks  the specified nets and their related pins as either special nets
       and pins, or regular nets and pins.

       When the Verilog list is first loaded into the design, all LEF pins ex-
       cept those with USE POWER and USE GROUND are considered "regular  pins"
       by  default,  and  are routed by Trial Route and NanoRoute. You can use
       this command to mark nets (and their pins) as special prior to  routing
       to  keep  NanoRoute  from attempting to route them. This is useful when
       you have nets that need to be routed by hand, or with other specialized
       routers.

       If you later decide you want the nets to be routed  by  NanoRoute,  you
       can use the setNet command to set them back to regular.

       Note: The setNet command has no effect if the net is already routed.

Parameters
       -help  Prints  a  brief  description that includes the type and default
              information for each setNet parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man setNet.

       -file <fileName>
              Changes all nets (and their related pins) in the specified  file
              to be either special or regular. The file must contain a list of
              net names, with one net name per line.

       -net <netName>
              Changes the specified net and its related pins to be either spe-
              cial or regular.

       -setTermSpecial
              Sets the term

       -type {regular | special}
              Specifies the type to which to change the net.

              regular:  Changes the net and its pins to a regular net, so that
              NanoRoute will route them.

              special: Changes the net and its pins to a special net  to  keep
              NanoRoute from attempting to route them.

Example
       The  following command sets the net myAnalogNet and its related pins as
       special:

       setNet -net myAnalogNet -type special -setTermSpecial

       The NanoRoute router ignores this net when routing.

